<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,828,2043]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1332,1358]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[330,591,1332,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luctuosus">
<emphasis box="[330,591,1332,1358]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Xanthopygus luctuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is (on average) the largest species in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kraatz" authorityYear="1857" box="[1026,1172,1332,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1026,1172,1332,1358]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Xanthopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but is rather similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[151,283,1368,1394]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oliveirae">
<emphasis box="[151,283,1368,1394]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">X. oliveirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These two species (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[519,657,1368,1394]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luctuosus">
<emphasis box="[519,657,1368,1394]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">X. luctuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[713,844,1368,1394]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oliveirae">
<emphasis box="[713,844,1368,1394]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">X. oliveirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) can be distinguished from all other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kraatz" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Xanthopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the following characters: antennomere 4 without tomentose pubescence; mandibles more or less straight except tip; eyes as long as 1/4 length of head; head appearing flat; and sternite 6 with two anterior transverse lines. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[218,477,1476,1502]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luctuosus">
<emphasis box="[218,477,1476,1502]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Xanthopygus luctuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[780,911,1476,1502]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oliveirae">
<emphasis box="[780,911,1476,1502]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">X. oliveirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the following: antennomere 3 clearly longer than 2 (antennomere 3 subequal to 
<quantity box="[631,675,1512,1539]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName box="[683,815,1512,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oliveirae">
<emphasis box="[683,815,1512,1538]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">X. oliveirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); pronotum microsculpture polygon shaped (pronotum microsculpture with transverse lines in 
<taxonomicName box="[588,719,1548,1574]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oliveirae">
<emphasis box="[588,719,1548,1574]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">X. oliveirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); and tergite 6 sparsely punctate (tergite 6 densely punctate in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oliveirae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">X. oliveirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,828,2043]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1620,1646]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Description.</emphasis>
Forebody length 
<quantity box="[546,705,1621,1647]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.485" metricValueMax="1.73" metricValueMin="1.24" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" unit="mm" value="14.85" valueMax="17.3" valueMin="12.4">12.4–17.3mm</quantity>
; HW/HL ratio = 1.31. Antennomere 3 clearly longer to 2; antennomere 4 subquadrate, without tomentose pubescence; antennomere 6 transverse. Mandibles more or less straight except apical tip. Eyes as long as 1/4 length of head; head appearing flat. Head and pronotum with small size punctures (see 
<figureCitation box="[322,459,1728,1755]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" captionTargetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[156,1432,181,1486]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Xanthopygus luctuosus (Blanchard). 15. Habitus photograph. 16. Pronotum. 17. Sternites 6–8. 18. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Figs. 15–16</figureCitation>
); pronotum with one sparse row of punctures on each half beside median line; pronotum microsculpture polygon shaped. PW/PL ratio = 1.12. Mesoventrite with intercoxal process broad and rounded. Metacoxae with more than four spines (five or six) on posterior surface. EL/PL ratio = 1.38. Abdominal segments 4–6 without iridescent overtones; segment 6 without distinct bright band of orange coloration posteriorly; tergite 6 sparsely punctate; sternite 6 with two anterior transverse lines; segment 7 orange. In males, sternite 7 without porose structure; sternite 8 with shallow U-shaped emargination posteriorly. Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[1190,1327,1908,1935]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–21" captionStartId="11.[151,264,782,806]" captionTargetBox="[197,1385,181,753]" captionTargetId="figure-16@11.[197,1390,181,758]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–21. Aedeagus of X. luctuosus (Blanchard). 19. Dorsal view. 20. Lateral view. 21. Detail of paramere, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048495/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Figs. 19–21</figureCitation>
; in dorsal view paramere straight; apex emarginate; paramere slightly shorter and narrower than median lobe; in lateral view paramere almost straight; paramere with peg setae as in 
<figureCitation box="[782,865,1980,2007]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–21" captionStartId="11.[151,264,782,806]" captionTargetBox="[197,1385,181,753]" captionTargetId="figure-16@11.[197,1390,181,758]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–21. Aedeagus of X. luctuosus (Blanchard). 19. Dorsal view. 20. Lateral view. 21. Detail of paramere, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048495/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
. Median lobe in dorsal view converging to pointed apex; median lobe with subapical tooth; in lateral view median lobe becoming narrower near apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" startId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" targetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" targetPageId="10">
